But these individual defects are amply compensated for by the good impression which the speech makes as a whole. It shows young Cicero still in the garb of innocence ; the deep conviction of the justice of his cause exalts and animates him as he speaks; none of his statements represent him as serving the interest of one party, or merely playing the advo· cate: in the consciousness of right he utterly forgets the powerful faction which stands opposed to him with scoffs and threats. And we should admire, no loss than the manly boldness with which he faccs his abandoned opponents, the moderation and prudence with which he avoids everything that can offend the all-powerful dictator.
